title Glow accepted, Tera to Triz, placeholder-ship-name rule, Glow supplement scoped
prompt Kaeden ruled to keep Glow as the fused language's name (framing it as fulfilling a dormant prior project's vision rather than competing with it), clarified the architecture as one language governed by one TAME document with four kernel variants written in it, named Riyo and Reya as an explicit diverse-redundancy pair, swapped Tera for Triz, asked for docs to use ship-name placeholders that are never real-network-valid rather than personal or Urbit-standard examples, and asked for Glow's fusion design to address runes, auras, "cold and warm atoms," structs/nouns, and Hoon-grade comment/line-width linting via an even stricter new TAME supplement.
think Verified rather than assumed Kaeden's factual claims about the existing Glow Language project — confirmed via web search that Glow-Lang/glow was created 2021, shows no recent commit activity signal, and its sibling repos (glow2-haskell, sexpr-parser) point at an S-expression/Scheme-rooted toolchain, consistent with Kaeden's read. Named plainly that I could not independently confirm the exact "11 months" figure to the day.
think Corrected "cold and warm atoms" to Urbit's real, documented term — cold/warm/hot jet *state*, not atoms — by checking docs.urbit.org's own jetting documentation directly rather than guessing at what Kaeden meant. Framed the correction as grounding, not a rebuke, and connected it directly to the jets.c/hashtable.c reading already done in the earlier Vere fusion study, so the correction adds understanding rather than just fixing a word.
think Ran a fresh collision search on Triz (the Tera replacement) rather than leaving the swap unchecked — found a real but low-stakes soft collision with TRIZ, the innovation methodology, with active current Python tooling. Assessed it as acceptable given the domain distance (patent-analysis methodology vs. a kernel variant) and said so plainly, without deciding on Kaeden's behalf.
think Designed the placeholder-ship-name safety rule around a single, checkable structural fact — every real Urbit syllable is exactly three letters — rather than trying to enumerate or avoid the full 256-entry syllable table. A rule anyone can verify by counting letters is more durable than one that depends on memorizing a reserved list.
think Named that Kaeden's own real ~bandun and ~pacpet-solreb, recorded in PUBKEYS.md from an earlier pass, are now explicitly protected by this same rule — never to appear as generic documentation examples, only in the identity record where naming them is the point.
think Scoped, rather than wrote, the Glow TAME supplement across five real surfaces (runes, auras, jet-state witnesses, structs-as-molds, Hoon-grade linting) — matching this session's own established pattern of researching and proposing before writing code or seating a change inside a heavily-cited file like TAME_GUIDANCE.md.
obs The four-kernel-variant architecture is now clearer than it was two passes ago (one language, one TAME document, four variants), but Trey/Triz's relationship to each other is still unconfirmed — Kaeden named Riyo/Reya's redundancy pairing explicitly and did not yet say the same of the second pair.
